<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-01T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-01T14:00:00-05:00" n="362" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d362">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2559:
                        Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                            the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-01T22:00:00+03:00">May 1, 1944—10
                                p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received May 2—1:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1535. See my 1514, April 29, 11 p.m. It seems likely that the inquiry made of
                        me at the Foreign Office on April 29 may have been related to the question
                        of the inclusion in Stalin’s May 1 order of the day of the warning to
                        Rumania, Hungary, Finland and Bulgaria to get out of the war.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hamilton</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>